+# --description--
+
+As you recall from earlier lessons and workshops, you can extract portions of a string by using the `slice()` method.
+
+Here is a reminder:
+
+```js
+const str = "abcd";
+str.slice(0, 3); // "abc"
+```
+
+Change the value of the `camelCasedVersion` from an empty string to the result of using the `slice()` method on the `lowercaseWord` variable. Pass in the number `0` and `5` which represent the start and end indices for the `slice()` method.
+
+Now you should see the word `"camel"` in the console.
+
+# --hints--
+
+Your `camelCasedVersion` variable should not be an empty string.
+
+```js
+assert.isNotEmpty(camelCasedVersion);
+```
+
+You should assign `lowercaseWord.slice(0, 5)` to the `camelCasedVersion` variable.
+
+```js
+assert.equal(camelCasedVersion, lowercaseWord.slice(0, 5));
+```
+
+You should NOT assign the literal string `"camel"` to the `camelCasedVersion`. Please reread through the instructions for the correct approach.
+
+```js
+assert.notMatch(code, /camelCasedVersion\s*=(["'])camel(["'])/);
+```
+
